@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xx) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a TYPE TEST (`r is Ok(v)` — a runtime tag check that also
-- binds the matched payload). eval evaluates the subject and returns a Bool from its
-- constructor tag (binding the payload in the `then` scope); the compute spine has no
-- type-test lowering — `normComp`/`norm` reach the `TypeTest` AST node and refuse it (the
-- `default` arm of `normComp`). The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a
-- CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals; D1(xvii) PAST `for`
-- comprehensions; D1(xviii) PAST integer ranges; D1(xix) PAST index assignment; D1(xx) PAST
-- the `loop` construct (`loop … break`/`continue`; see compile_loop_test). The frontier now
-- sits at TYPE TESTS (`e is Ctor(binder)`). This file uses one, so it still refuses; when
-- type tests lower (a later D1 slice, a tag compare + payload bind), it flips from
-- `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def describe(r: Result(Number, String)): String
  if r is Ok(v)
    "got {v}"
  else
    "err"

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(describe(Ok(5)))
  println(describe(Error("bad")))
